WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.260 --> 00:00:04.460
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:07.130 --> 00:00:09.796
&gt;&gt; I first met David
Remnick 22 years ago

00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:12.640
when he was just a wisp of a boy.

00:00:13.240 --> 00:00:17.040
I was something of a wisp
myself but I decided to call him

00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:19.320
up when I heard that he had just
been made the Moscow correspondent

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:24.040
for the Washington Post.

00:00:24.870 --> 00:00:25.030
He had come into that
position out of nowhere.

00:00:27.710 --> 00:00:32.310
He had graduated from Princeton just
six years before and gone to work

00:00:33.090 --> 00:00:37.090
for the Post as a night beat
police reporter, I think it was.

00:00:37.650 --> 00:00:41.650
In time he graduated to covering
the National Football League

00:00:41.870 --> 00:00:42.870
for the paper.

00:00:43.870 --> 00:00:43.910
But now he was studying
Russian intently

00:00:46.430 --> 00:00:49.030
and I being an enterprising
young editor

00:00:49.470 --> 00:00:53.070
at a New York publishing
house decided to introduce him

00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:53.973
to an author whose book I was about
to publish, the very talented,

00:00:57.360 --> 00:01:00.626
irrepressibly decedent,
devastatingly acute master

00:01:01.980 --> 00:01:04.380
of Soviet Satire, Vladimir
Voinovich.

00:01:06.340 --> 00:01:08.006
I invited David to lunch.

00:01:08.510 --> 00:01:10.910
We met at-- I think
it was Galileo's.

00:01:12.270 --> 00:01:16.270
Voinovich who barely spoke
English took to David immediately.

00:01:17.190 --> 00:01:18.790
It was a chemical thing.

00:01:19.410 --> 00:01:19.676
David who didn't know much Russian
at the time returned the compliment.

00:01:23.810 --> 00:01:25.276
They liked each other.

00:01:25.810 --> 00:01:27.543
They later became friends.

00:01:28.060 --> 00:01:32.326
It was clear that this nascent
foreign correspondent was a bright

00:01:32.970 --> 00:01:36.836
and curious young man, a
reporter who watched and listened.

00:01:38.340 --> 00:01:43.073
And even at that early point of his
career, it was clear he was a person

00:01:43.150 --> 00:01:45.416
who could look past current events

00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:48.400
to the deeper human
issues that drive them.

00:01:49.540 --> 00:01:52.606
It's been a pleasure to
watch David ever since.

00:01:52.980 --> 00:01:56.513
Obviously he mastered Russian
so expertly that he went

00:01:56.830 --> 00:01:57.370
on to cover the historic events
of the crumbling Soviet Union

00:02:00.290 --> 00:02:02.623
with great sensitivity and insight.

00:02:03.680 --> 00:02:06.080
When communism collapsed
and glasnost

00:02:07.760 --> 00:02:09.693
and perestroika surprised us,

00:02:10.170 --> 00:02:13.770
David Remnick was among the
few who could explain them.

00:02:14.540 --> 00:02:18.206
Eventually he wrote a very
good book called Lenin's Tomb

00:02:18.380 --> 00:02:21.646
which won the 1994 Pulitzer
Prize for non fiction.

00:02:22.170 --> 00:02:23.836
He was only 36 years old.

00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:25.500
He had joined the New
Yorker by then.

00:02:27.580 --> 00:02:29.846
For a while he was a staff writer.

00:02:29.930 --> 00:02:34.596
Within six years he succeeded Tina
Brown as the editor of the magazine.

00:02:35.030 --> 00:02:35.570
In the interim, he has been
credited with increasing circulation

00:02:38.690 --> 00:02:42.690
by 23 percent to more than a
million readers, and he is loved

00:02:45.100 --> 00:02:45.110
by his writers and editors and
the marketers on his staff,

00:02:48.890 --> 00:02:51.890
all of whom feel he lives
only to please them.

00:02:53.680 --> 00:02:55.613
Writer, editor and publisher,

00:02:56.480 --> 00:02:56.780
David has written six
books and edited four more.

00:02:59.380 --> 00:03:01.246
How he does it is a mystery.

00:03:01.710 --> 00:03:02.310
Although Malcolm Gladwell,
a New Yorker staff writer

00:03:04.510 --> 00:03:04.523
and a fellow book writer once said,

00:03:06.830 --> 00:03:09.430
"He likes to pretend
that it's no sweat.

00:03:10.850 --> 00:03:11.126
He cruises around and chats
with people and then disappears

00:03:14.440 --> 00:03:17.306
and writes thousands
of words in 15 minutes.

00:03:17.920 --> 00:03:21.120
It's all a part of that
make it look easy thing."

00:03:21.710 --> 00:03:22.430
When asked how he could
possibly write a revealing book

00:03:24.590 --> 00:03:27.590
about President Barack
Obama and still run one

00:03:28.180 --> 00:03:28.450
of the most successful magazines
in the country, his wife,

00:03:31.710 --> 00:03:34.176
a writer with the New
York Times said,

00:03:34.300 --> 00:03:38.766
"He got up really early went back
to work after dinner with the kids

00:03:39.040 --> 00:03:43.173
and took no weekends off and no
vacations for more than a year.

00:03:44.560 --> 00:03:48.960
The result has been a fascinating
book that describes our president

00:03:49.200 --> 00:03:52.866
as a man for all seasons, a
flexible mutable chameleon."

00:03:55.940 --> 00:03:58.406
As the Post's reviewer
for book world,

00:03:58.640 --> 00:04:02.840
Gwen Ifill of PBS described it,
"Remnick efficiently strips some

00:04:03.960 --> 00:04:06.693
of the gloss off the
version Obama offered

00:04:07.400 --> 00:04:11.600
in his best selling 1995 memoir
Dreams from my Father charitably

00:04:12.640 --> 00:04:12.846
and accurately describing
that effort as a mixture

00:04:15.700 --> 00:04:18.633
of verifiable fact,
recollection, recreation,

00:04:20.060 --> 00:04:22.060
invention and artful shaping."

00:04:23.030 --> 00:04:23.653
Here to talk about that book
and to illumine his theories

00:04:26.140 --> 00:04:28.140
and observations about our man

00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:29.206
in the White House is
the author of The Bridge.

00:04:30.140 --> 00:04:30.546
Please welcome one of our most
dynamic American journalists

00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:34.600
David Remnick.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:36.000


00:04:36.100 --> 00:04:37.100
[ Applause ]

00:04:43.750 --> 00:04:46.283
&gt;&gt; I need to offer
two corrections as--

00:04:46.740 --> 00:04:51.206
I guess if you're an editor you
edit everything I just I'm extremely

00:04:51.320 --> 00:04:51.730
pleased by and flattered
by that introduction.

00:04:53.910 --> 00:04:56.110
Let me offer two corrections one,

00:04:56.650 --> 00:04:57.516
I did not cover the
National Football League

00:04:58.650 --> 00:04:58.916
that would have been the Redskins.

00:05:00.650 --> 00:05:00.783
That was way too exalted for me.

00:05:02.650 --> 00:05:05.450
I covered the United
States Football League

00:05:05.590 --> 00:05:08.256
and the team was the
Washington Federals.

00:05:08.800 --> 00:05:11.066
A league that you now sadly forget

00:05:13.050 --> 00:05:15.850
and the team went I
think two and fourteen.

00:05:16.590 --> 00:05:20.923
And it rained every Sunday and
that was-- that was my other thing.

00:05:20.990 --> 00:05:21.150
The other thing is the notion
of the no sweat business.

00:05:24.430 --> 00:05:25.460
I think we can all agree safely
that this is the Schmitz capital

00:05:27.600 --> 00:05:28.503
of the world [laughter] and let's
give ourselves a little applause

00:05:31.030 --> 00:05:33.030
for enduring it so [applause].

00:05:34.470 --> 00:05:38.136
And I want to thank all the
organizers of this festival.

00:05:39.130 --> 00:05:41.396
I think you can't really imagine--

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:42.143
I think we can vaguely imagine why
readers would want to come here

00:05:46.190 --> 00:05:46.273
and listen to Stacy Schiff or
Jon Franzen or Will Haygood

00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:54.373
or whoever they happen to see in
the last hours with great enjoyment.

00:05:55.210 --> 00:05:58.210
But you have to know
what it does for writers,

00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:02.386
to see people that actually read,
read you, have things to say

00:06:03.600 --> 00:06:04.960
about these books-- critical
things to say about these books,

00:06:06.240 --> 00:06:08.773
complimentary things
about these books.

00:06:09.150 --> 00:06:13.283
Reading is an extraordinary
activity done in quiet and solitude

00:06:15.620 --> 00:06:18.086
as Jon Franzen has
said recently you--

00:06:18.920 --> 00:06:22.986
reading is the one thing you
can't do seriously and multitask.

00:06:23.170 --> 00:06:26.036
Occasions like this
though, well not reading

00:06:26.590 --> 00:06:27.360
and maybe secondary activities are
really important to writers once

00:06:30.220 --> 00:06:31.540
in a while to get out of the
house and meet their readers.

00:06:32.700 --> 00:06:34.633
It does a lot for us, I know.

00:06:34.900 --> 00:06:36.500
So I thank you for that.

00:06:36.900 --> 00:06:38.403
I wanted-- I have just a few minutes
that I want to talk about this book

00:06:40.130 --> 00:06:43.596
and maybe provoke a short
discussion with you and see

00:06:44.570 --> 00:06:46.370
if I can manage to do that.

00:06:46.570 --> 00:06:47.333
I just-- I should say a little bit
about the origins of this book,

00:06:50.140 --> 00:06:50.156
question that I get very often has
Barack Obama wrote an autobiography?

00:06:54.790 --> 00:06:59.590
Yes I know that, and even an awfully
good autobiography and a second book

00:07:00.310 --> 00:07:03.243
as well that has some
virtues and also some--

00:07:03.350 --> 00:07:05.216
I think it was utility book.

00:07:05.360 --> 00:07:05.736
But the first book is
actually good book.

00:07:07.650 --> 00:07:07.850
It tells a lot about of his life.

00:07:09.650 --> 00:07:09.656
Why would you bother
writing a biography?

00:07:12.310 --> 00:07:15.910
Well first of all,
autobiographies, memoirs are stories

00:07:16.780 --> 00:07:18.713
that you tell about yourself.

00:07:18.930 --> 00:07:19.630
It has the point of view of
your-- your own point of view.

00:07:22.030 --> 00:07:24.963
You leave in and take
out what you want to do

00:07:25.200 --> 00:07:25.600
and you would no more consider a
book on Ben Franklin authoritative

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:29.716
if it was called the
autobiography of Ben Franklin

00:07:31.950 --> 00:07:32.423
as you would imagine it if it were
written by the man in the moon.

00:07:35.810 --> 00:07:38.810
Ben Franklin is a book
that requires all kinds

00:07:38.840 --> 00:07:42.906
of biographical scholarship and
pressure from brands and shift

00:07:42.970 --> 00:07:43.873
and all the many people
who have concentrated

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:46.866
on it from different angles.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:51.200
And an emerging political figure
like Barack Obama who makes use

00:07:51.470 --> 00:07:54.336
of his own life, the
story o f his own life,

00:07:55.110 --> 00:07:57.910
and makes it into a
political utility even,

00:07:58.890 --> 00:08:00.756
bears biographical scholarly

00:08:01.920 --> 00:08:04.920
and journalistic pressure
that is not his own.

00:08:05.250 --> 00:08:08.116
So the idea to do that
book is not something

00:08:08.760 --> 00:08:09.226
that really required
a lot of thought.

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:11.220
But I didn't know how much
room there was for maneuver.

00:08:13.900 --> 00:08:17.300
As an editor and as a friend
of John Updike's I went

00:08:18.070 --> 00:08:20.603
to his funeral a couple
of winters ago.

00:08:22.120 --> 00:08:25.253
And on the way back from
the Massachusetts shore

00:08:26.100 --> 00:08:29.500
where this funeral took
place, a very small service.

00:08:29.580 --> 00:08:29.846
I stopped in at Harvard Law School

00:08:31.580 --> 00:08:32.013
and spent a few days interviewing
law professors and colleagues

00:08:35.280 --> 00:08:38.213
of Obama's just to see
what there was to know

00:08:39.970 --> 00:08:40.973
after all the campaign had been
going on for quite a long time.

00:08:43.100 --> 00:08:43.700
Many, many stories
had been written some

00:08:45.100 --> 00:08:45.366
by some very talented journalists.

00:08:47.100 --> 00:08:50.966
What was left over, and that
little experiment proved to me

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:51.766
that there was a story to tell,
a story that hadn't been told,

00:08:54.300 --> 00:08:56.500
a story that required some depth.

00:08:59.630 --> 00:09:02.430
Barack-- one of the
chapters in The Bridge,

00:09:02.520 --> 00:09:06.720
the book obviously is a biography
and set against the background

00:09:07.230 --> 00:09:11.763
and context of the racial drama of
the nation's politics and it takes

00:09:15.150 --> 00:09:19.416
in quite a lot everything from
Harold Washington and the politics

00:09:20.280 --> 00:09:23.346
of Chicago, the politics
of Harvard Law School,

00:09:23.440 --> 00:09:27.373
the history of African-Americans
running for the presidency,

00:09:27.500 --> 00:09:31.300
many different kind of subplots
in the course of the book.

00:09:32.500 --> 00:09:36.633
But I also spent a chapter looking
at Obama's own autobiography

00:09:39.260 --> 00:09:42.060
as a specimen of probably
the richest genre

00:09:43.890 --> 00:09:48.090
of African-American writing and
that is African-American memoir.

00:09:48.580 --> 00:09:52.713
In other words, I wanted to see
how this book which was written

00:09:53.390 --> 00:09:53.666
in relative innocence, in other
words, before he became a candidate.

00:09:57.580 --> 00:09:57.913
Before that time when
politicians write nonsense books

00:10:00.780 --> 00:10:04.913
about themselves and bland books
about their political policies

00:10:07.610 --> 00:10:08.073
and biographies that try to
appeal to everybody all at once.

00:10:11.080 --> 00:10:14.746
&gt;&gt; This is a book written in
relative innocence and also

00:10:15.050 --> 00:10:17.450
out of a sense of literary ambition.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.400
The origins of his
autobiography come

00:10:20.650 --> 00:10:24.116
when a literary agent notices
an article on the press

00:10:24.150 --> 00:10:24.960
that this guy has become the
first African-American president

00:10:27.340 --> 00:10:29.073
of the Harvard Law Review.

00:10:29.340 --> 00:10:31.340
She asked him to write a book.

00:10:31.340 --> 00:10:32.006
He doesn't know what
he's going to write.

00:10:33.340 --> 00:10:34.806
He thinks about writing a
book about Civil Rights Law

00:10:35.340 --> 00:10:35.993
and he happens upon his
own story and writes it.

00:10:37.820 --> 00:10:37.910
Just like Michelle Laurice or any
number of other African-Americans

00:10:42.130 --> 00:10:44.063
who ventured into this genre.

00:10:44.810 --> 00:10:45.190
And I tried to look at
this book structurally,

00:10:47.430 --> 00:10:50.496
what it sets out to do,
taking note of the fact

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:51.063
that there are three parts
to it, each of them ends

00:10:54.310 --> 00:10:55.976
with the author in tears.

00:10:56.670 --> 00:10:58.870
And it's structured apolitically.

00:11:00.460 --> 00:11:00.780
It's in a political context but
it is not a candidate's book.

00:11:04.140 --> 00:11:04.533
It does not take into account
Obama's life in politics

00:11:07.280 --> 00:11:10.080
as he enters the world
of Chicago politics.

00:11:12.430 --> 00:11:15.363
So, that was how I set
out writing this book.

00:11:16.150 --> 00:11:20.216
I had no interest in trying to
play a catch up game of writing

00:11:21.070 --> 00:11:22.870
about the Obama presidency.

00:11:23.070 --> 00:11:23.236
The book ends at the
White House door.

00:11:25.370 --> 00:11:29.636
And it examines him in all regards
prior not only to the election

00:11:32.770 --> 00:11:33.543
but even the campaign itself gets
fairly short tripped compared

00:11:36.130 --> 00:11:36.193
to these episodes in
Obama's youth and childhood

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:41.066
in his parent's development.

00:11:41.400 --> 00:11:45.733
I just want to say one thing about
African-American autobiography,

00:11:46.480 --> 00:11:46.836
something that it has very-- in
a very generalized way, in common

00:11:50.390 --> 00:11:52.790
and in common with Obama's own book.

00:11:54.620 --> 00:11:58.220
If you look at African-American
autobiography, a genre,

00:11:59.030 --> 00:12:03.096
that begins with 6000 slave
narratives, I mean the most famous

00:12:04.420 --> 00:12:05.706
of which is Frederick Douglas but
there are thousands of other ones,

00:12:07.600 --> 00:12:11.066
a genre that goes straight
through to the great books

00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:15.813
of the 20th Century, we know whether
it's Richard Wright or Malcolm X

00:12:15.850 --> 00:12:20.383
or Maya Angelou, so many of them,
they have certain things in common,

00:12:22.980 --> 00:12:27.580
a struggle for freedom, a journey
from either incarceration or slavery

00:12:29.180 --> 00:12:29.383
or oppression or stifling
depending on the period of time

00:12:32.710 --> 00:12:36.710
and historical circumstances,
a journey that tends to be part

00:12:37.550 --> 00:12:41.216
of this and a search for
community, a search for a self,

00:12:42.250 --> 00:12:43.850
a search for a politics,

00:12:44.250 --> 00:12:45.426
and a search for geography
and a sense of purpose.

00:12:46.340 --> 00:12:49.873
All these things are present
in Obama's autobiography.

00:12:51.510 --> 00:12:56.043
The book of which-- some reviewers
have used the euphemism exhaustive

00:12:57.060 --> 00:12:58.526
to describe this book.

00:12:59.280 --> 00:13:01.813
What they mean is it
is 600 pages long.

00:13:02.580 --> 00:13:05.313
And maybe occasionally
they got exhausted.

00:13:05.680 --> 00:13:06.610
But what the goal of the book is to
separate the wheat from the chaff,

00:13:09.350 --> 00:13:12.616
the myth from-- realities
from myths, the nonsense

00:13:13.570 --> 00:13:17.303
and the conspiracy theories
from the facts of the matter.

00:13:18.160 --> 00:13:21.960
It's an active journalism and
a journalism that took place

00:13:22.260 --> 00:13:26.726
and I hope to get it out while Obama
was still in office, believe it

00:13:26.960 --> 00:13:27.433
or not, not for commercial reasons
but as part of the project itself,

00:13:31.020 --> 00:13:31.506
part of knowing a president
and a president's life

00:13:33.800 --> 00:13:36.333
as best one can while
he was in office.

00:13:36.660 --> 00:13:38.860
And here we are a year and a half

00:13:39.620 --> 00:13:42.286
into the presidency
and what has sunk in?

00:13:43.880 --> 00:13:46.946
Over 20 percent of the
American public believes

00:13:50.730 --> 00:13:55.463
that Barack Obama is a Muslim as if
there were anything wrong with that,

00:13:55.870 --> 00:13:56.003
but believes that he's a Muslim.

00:13:57.870 --> 00:14:01.403
We still-- any audience that
I go to were very often--

00:14:02.220 --> 00:14:03.123
I'm still asked about birth
certificates, was he really born

00:14:05.250 --> 00:14:08.983
in Hawaii, in other words the
very fact of his existence,

00:14:10.120 --> 00:14:10.190
his national existence is brought

00:14:12.250 --> 00:14:15.383
under serious question
despite all the necessary

00:14:16.520 --> 00:14:18.520
and requisite proof otherwise.

00:14:19.080 --> 00:14:23.546
Haley Barbour, who distinguished
himself actually during Katrina one

00:14:23.700 --> 00:14:27.366
of very few politicians who
did was interviewed recently

00:14:27.430 --> 00:14:28.350
and it's maybe not by
mistake that he's mentioned

00:14:29.710 --> 00:14:30.620
as a possible presidential
candidate in a couple of years.

00:14:32.600 --> 00:14:36.400
He said that Barack Obama was
somehow, remains mysterious,

00:14:36.920 --> 00:14:40.053
that we don't know very
much about Barack Obama.

00:14:40.150 --> 00:14:40.383
Rush Limbaugh plays this
violin all the time,

00:14:42.850 --> 00:14:43.783
Glenn Beck I need not
tell you plays this violin

00:14:45.050 --> 00:14:48.650
and recently Dinesh D'Souza,
conservative intellectual,

00:14:48.910 --> 00:14:49.270
you probably know has
come out with an article

00:14:51.550 --> 00:14:55.883
in Fortune Magazine prefatory to
a book that's coming and proposes

00:14:56.520 --> 00:15:00.986
that Barack Obama sees the world
through a post colonial canon point

00:15:01.240 --> 00:15:04.773
of view and this is a view
endorsed by as brilliant by

00:15:07.770 --> 00:15:11.503
yet another possibility for
the presidency Newt Gingrich.

00:15:12.830 --> 00:15:16.630
And I think it is too polite
to distinguish these theories

00:15:21.210 --> 00:15:21.740
and these points of
view with anything more

00:15:23.480 --> 00:15:25.146
than a most harsh answer.

00:15:25.580 --> 00:15:25.810
The fact of the matter
is Obama's born--

00:15:27.950 --> 00:15:32.016
Barack Obama's life hides in
plain sight as does his ideology,

00:15:33.330 --> 00:15:35.530
he is the man of the center left.

00:15:35.630 --> 00:15:38.563
He is somebody born
where he says he is born,

00:15:38.570 --> 00:15:38.626
very much had the life
he says he has.

00:15:40.980 --> 00:15:44.446
Does he know people that
were way to the left of him?

00:15:45.300 --> 00:15:45.516
Yes. Does he know people and learn
from people way to the right of him?

00:15:49.750 --> 00:15:50.230
In law school he studied both with
Charles Fried and Roberto Unger.

00:15:53.670 --> 00:15:56.403
That didn't make him
a Brazilian socialist

00:15:56.440 --> 00:15:59.573
and that didn't make him
a right wing republican

00:16:00.740 --> 00:16:02.673
in the mold of Charles Fried.

00:16:02.740 --> 00:16:03.240
He is somebody that read
the books of Richard Posner

00:16:05.640 --> 00:16:07.506
and was a research assistant

00:16:08.010 --> 00:16:10.810
for a great liberal
constitutional scholar.

00:16:11.470 --> 00:16:13.270
This doesn't make him them.

00:16:13.470 --> 00:16:15.936
His associations do
not make him them.

00:16:16.670 --> 00:16:20.070
And yet for political
reasons certain intellectuals,

00:16:22.710 --> 00:16:25.443
certain politicians,
certain media outlets

00:16:26.040 --> 00:16:29.106
and myriad websites
continue to play this tune.

00:16:30.010 --> 00:16:30.793
I referred earlier and I'll
make this a concluding point,

00:16:32.960 --> 00:16:37.293
I referred earlier to the genre
of African-American autobiography.

00:16:38.200 --> 00:16:41.933
One of the distinguishing
features of slave narratives is

00:16:42.990 --> 00:16:45.723
that slaves wrote to
prove their literacy,

00:16:46.500 --> 00:16:48.900
their personhood, their
independence.

00:16:49.600 --> 00:16:53.133
And yet they had to have
very often the books endorsed

00:16:54.310 --> 00:16:55.843
by white abolitionists.

00:16:57.520 --> 00:16:59.453
If you look at the title page

00:16:59.520 --> 00:17:02.920
of Frederick Douglas'
autobiography it has a gesture

00:17:03.610 --> 00:17:04.276
from William Lloyd Garrison saying
this book was actually written

00:17:07.210 --> 00:17:09.943
by believe it or not
by Frederick Douglas.

00:17:11.770 --> 00:17:14.436
That's where we were
in the 19th Century.

00:17:16.050 --> 00:17:20.583
And yet on the internet, on Rush
Limbaugh and elsewhere there cropped

00:17:22.040 --> 00:17:22.203
up the theory that Barack
Obama wasn't even capable

00:17:25.210 --> 00:17:27.476
of writing the book that he wrote.

00:17:27.640 --> 00:17:28.493
We heard theories that Barack
Obama was not the author

00:17:30.320 --> 00:17:31.186
of his own biography
but who was its author?

00:17:32.320 --> 00:17:33.986
Wait for it-- Bill Ayers.

00:17:35.910 --> 00:17:36.313
Well if this was just one
isolated website it wouldn't worth

00:17:39.440 --> 00:17:40.076
distinguishing in an audience like
this but that is where we are,

00:17:43.070 --> 00:17:43.083
and Barack Obama's life is still
in play as a political weapon.

